@wbond, regarding the `dict` as a `core.Choice`, you may have felt bad with it, but it is actually the most natural way...

Let's focus on an example:

```
# Current construction:
'recipient_infos': [
    cms.RecipientInfo(
        name='ktri',
        value={
            'version': u'v0',
            'rid': cms.RecipientIdentifier(
                name='issuer_and_serial_number',
                value=issuer
            ),
            # ...
        }
    )
]

# Look how fluent it could be:
'recipient_infos': [
    { 'ktri': {
        'version': u'v0',
        'rid': { 'issuer_and_serial_number': issuer },
        # ...
    }
]
```

I see a `core.Choice` as a special form of `core.Sequence`, where a single "attribute" exists (the attribute name defines the type of the value). Maybe the possible confusion is that when creating a `dict` for a `core.Choice` the developer may end up specifying more than one attribute, which in such a case you may easily raise an exception. Similarly, the developer may pass a `tuple` with more than 2 elements...

The code below is not as fluent to me as the above, but it is certainly better than the original:

```
# Using tuple:
'recipient_infos': [
    ( 'ktri', {
        'version': u'v0',
        'rid': ( 'issuer_and_serial_number', issuer ),
        # ...
    )
]
```

Whatever way you improve will be much better than now.

