another question, this time regarding the behavior of populate.

my understanding was that the expected usage is:
```
    ParameterCollection m;
    Parameter a = m.add_parameters({10});
    Parameter b = m.add_parameters({3,7});
    Parameter c = m.add_parameters({2});
    dynet::Packer s("bla");
    s.save(m)
    //...

   ParameterCollection m2;
   Parameter a1 = m.add_parameters({10});
   Parameter b1 = m.add_parameters({3,7});
   Parameter c1 = m.add_parameters({2});
   dynet::Packer s2("bla");
   s2.populate(m2)
   // now a1 should be equal to a, b1 to b, c1 to c
```

However, this does not seem to be the case at all: if I understand correctly, the populate method adds new parameters to the model and not reusing existing ones.

Moreover, the tests have:
```
BOOST_AUTO_TEST_CASE ( test_save_load_parameter_collection ) {
  {
    ParameterCollection m;
    Parameter a = m.add_parameters({10}, "a");
    Parameter b = m.add_parameters({3,7});
    LookupParameter c = m.add_lookup_parameters(10, {2});
    std::remove("test.model"); std::remove("test.model.meta");
    dynet::Packer s("test.model");
    s.save(m, "model1");
    s.save(m, m.get_namespace(), true);

    ParameterCollection m2;
    s.populate(m2, "model1");
    DYNET_CHECK_EQUAL(m2, m);
    ParameterCollection m3;
    s.populate(m3, "/");
  }
```
notice that this is populating the collections `m2` and `m3` that do not have any parameters in them yet.
how is one supposed to access the parameters in `m2` and `m3` then?

